# 

<span key="3f42ff26c9934ffdae3602229608166b">**Notes**</span>

## 

<span key="62385af7c9cd40109d9b14bed8bae79f">**The Object Type**</span>

<span key="bd5cb50b38f24ac7b359c8c5423cea8a"><span offset-key="bd5cb50b38f24ac7b359c8c5423cea8a:0">The </span>**`object`**<span offset-key="bd5cb50b38f24ac7b359c8c5423cea8a:2"> is a data structure that stores other data, similar to how an array stores elements.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="72e72223e6814871a0952d2b4e3d372a"><span offset-key="72e72223e6814871a0952d2b4e3d372a:0">The object differs in that each </span>**`value`**<span offset-key="72e72223e6814871a0952d2b4e3d372a:2"> stores in an obj is associated with a </span>**`key`**<span offset-key="72e72223e6814871a0952d2b4e3d372a:4">.</span></span>

<span key="59b017641e9547158d427c5a5d9deae6">**The Object of My Affections**</span>

<span key="70406a3ccbbf4a6087c49f8204dd623c"><span offset-key="70406a3ccbbf4a6087c49f8204dd623c:0">In other programming languages, objects are referred to as, "dictionaries", "maps", or "associative arrays".</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="8e42f6ad4ecb4db684c74b7b471ca7d3"><span offset-key="8e42f6ad4ecb4db684c74b7b471ca7d3:0">Objects are indexed with </span>**`keys`**<span offset-key="8e42f6ad4ecb4db684c74b7b471ca7d3:2"> instead of numbers.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="069bdd18168a4bd2b54806dc68f9bf12"><span offset-key="069bdd18168a4bd2b54806dc68f9bf12:0">Order is not guaranteed within an Object.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="3291b30fc0da42bda1c7356d29930652"><span offset-key="3291b30fc0da42bda1c7356d29930652:0">Objects are defined by using curly braces </span>**`{}`**</span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="34d97f161296460f9afef0e4ff68baae"><span offset-key="34d97f161296460f9afef0e4ff68baae:0">You can think of Objects as tables.</span></span>

## 

<span key="76a440dd155c46a8a304325bf1e9b894">**References vs Primitives**</span>

<span key="85ef1af83b1a44dda7895252796a1133">**Primitives vs Objects**</span>

<span key="abbaed39cf344841ac6466c9648dfe51"><span offset-key="abbaed39cf344841ac6466c9648dfe51:0">So far we have learned about 6 different data types:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

    <span key="48c604c25a8846efa924780754680eab">**Primitive**<span offset-key="48c604c25a8846efa924780754680eab:1"> : Boolean, Null, Undefined, Number, String.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

    <span key="02b9614353bb40309d834c4d33133a80">**Reference**<span offset-key="02b9614353bb40309d834c4d33133a80:1"> : Object (Arrays are a type of object)</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

    <span key="5b68e59dbfaa46f08ce4be4a0a6e2dcf"><span offset-key="5b68e59dbfaa46f08ce4be4a0a6e2dcf:0">Remember that </span>**primitive**<span offset-key="5b68e59dbfaa46f08ce4be4a0a6e2dcf:2"> types are immutable!</span></span>

<span key="5a523d44d1674c6489980bf5196906d4">**Immutabiity**</span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

    <span key="0e4647a7e164433eb0b70e50d31fcc23"><span offset-key="0e4647a7e164433eb0b70e50d31fcc23:0">When we reassign primitives we simply have our variable point elsewhere in memory.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

    <span key="33d9ae254e474fd483e27680e2263f7a"><span offset-key="33d9ae254e474fd483e27680e2263f7a:0">In a nutshell, </span>**immutability**<span offset-key="33d9ae254e474fd483e27680e2263f7a:2"> cannot change values in memory, but only reassign where our variables are pointing to.</span></span>

<span key="7ebf36b32d3a4892b515d25f2b4461b2">**Mutabulity**</span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

    <span key="176b06eaa46c48df853bcd6d82c8cf6e"><span offset-key="176b06eaa46c48df853bcd6d82c8cf6e:0">If we change either cat1 or cat2, our computer memory will change because they are both pointing at the same memory location.</span></span>
